2star  aThe making, eating, and sharing of food throughout society represents an important and exciting area of study with the potential to advance the field of scholarship, particularly in the context of Scandinavian Studies. This book analyses the historical, legal, and literary sources of the region during the medieval period to explore different aspects of Scandinavian culture relating to food and drink: production, consumption (including feasts), trading (distribution), and the associated social rituals. Using new and innovative approaches, this collection of studies offers broad insights into a great variety of social practices and includes fresh information on not only social history but also traditional topics such as trade, commercial exchange, legal regulation, and political organisation. The book unites contributors from a variety of backgrounds, further enriching the content of a collection that promises to make a significant contribution to the state of current research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDinners and diningzScandinaviaxHistory. 0aFood habitszScandinaviaxHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFood Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aScandinavia, Sagas, Feasting, Vikings, Medieval History.1 aCeolin, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFigenschow, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyönki, Viktória, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyönki, Viktória, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKjesrud, Karoline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavender, Philip, 